2. Destructuring Objects¶

In [ ]:
%%script node


const player = {
  name: 'Lebron James',
  club: 'LA Lakers',
  address: {
    city: 'Los Angeles'
  }
};

// Getting values, the old way
console.log( player.address.city );

Los Angeles
In [ ]:
%%script node

const player = {
  name: 'Lebron James',
  club: 'LA Lakers',
  address: {
    city: 'Los Angeles'
  }
};


// Getting values, using object destructuring
const {name, club, address:{ city } } = player;

console.log('name:', name);
console.log('club:', club);
console.log('city:', city);
console.log('address', address) // this is error because we do not save `address` to a const

name: Lebron James
club: LA Lakers
city: Los Angeles
  • The old way to get value from an object is using object.key syntax.
  • The new way is to destructure the object. Eg const {key1, key2, key3: {nestedKey1} } = object
    • now, we can use [key1, key2, nestedKey1] as normal variable

3. Destructuring Arrays¶

  • We can destructure array similar to how we would do an object. The difference is now, we use [] instead of {}.
  • The syntax is: let [elem1, elem2, elemN] = array
  • What will happen is that the variable we destructure each of the elements into is actually a pointer, pointing to the index of the array.
  • So, in the example above, elem1 is a pointer pointing to the first index of the array, ie array[0].
    • elem2 is a pointer pointing to array[1] and so on.
In [12]:
%%script node

// desctruturing an array
author = ['Jane', 'Eyre', 'Rochester'] 
let [firstName, middleName, lastName] = author 

console.log('firstName:', firstName)
console.log('middleName:', middleName)
console.log('lastName:', lastName)

firstName: Jane
middleName: Eyre
lastName: Rochester

4. Object Literal¶

  • When creating an object with value having the same name as the variable name of the object, we can omit writing the key.
  • For example, say we store a value in variable called city and we want to create an object with key city.
    • The old way of doing this (see example 1): {city: city}
    • The new way of doing this (see example 2): {city}
    • Both give the same result.
In [ ]:
%%script node


function addressMaker(city, state) {

    // Example 1: old way
    const newAddress = {city: city, state: state}
    console.log(newAddress)
}

addressMaker('Austin', 'Texas');

{ city: 'Austin', state: 'Texas' }
In [ ]:
%%script node

function addressMaker(city, state) {

    // Example 2: using object literal
    const newAddress = {city, state}
    console.log(newAddress)
}

addressMaker('Austin', 'Texas');

{ city: 'Austin', state: 'Texas' }

5. For of Loop¶

In [2]:
%%script node

let incomes = [62000, 67000, 75000];
let total = 0;

for (const income of incomes) {
    console.log(income);
    total += income;
}

console.log('total:', total)

62000
67000
75000
total: 204000
In [ ]:
%%script node
const students = [ 
    { name: "John", city: "New York" },
    { name: "Peter", city: "Paris"},
    { name: "Kate", city: "Sidney" }
]

for (const stu of students) {
    // destructuring object
    const {name, city} = stu;
    console.log(`${name} lives in ${city}`)
}

John lives in New York
Peter lives in Paris
Kate lives in Sidney

6. Spread Operator¶

  • We can use spread operator to make copy of an iterable.
  • To make a copy of an array, we use syntaxt [ ...array ]
  • We can also add something to the array we are copying while using the spread operator.
    • To add to the front of the copied array before the entire content of the array we are copying, we use: [ newElem, ...array]
    • To add to the end, we do: [...array, newElem]
    • So, the general syntax is just same as we would building an array, separate each element by a comma ,.
    • I think it is easier to think of JS spread operator as list concatenation in python. 
(See example below)
// JS
myNewArray = [ newElem, ...array, newElem ]

// python equivalent
myNewArray = [newElem] + array + [newElem]
  • We can also use spread operator with objects. The syntax is the same, but instead of it be within a [], we do it in a {}. See last example below.

Code Example 1: Python equivalent of spread operator is list concatenation

In [ ]:
oldArray = ['Mary', 'Joel', 'Danny']

# this operation create a new array and not a pointer to oldarray 
newArray = ["myBoss"] + oldArray + ["myCEO"]
print('newArray:', newArray)

# note that this latest addition is not in the newArray
oldArray.append('myNeighbor')
print('newArray:', newArray)

newArray: ['myBoss', 'Mary', 'Joel', 'Danny', 'myCEO']
newArray: ['myBoss', 'Mary', 'Joel', 'Danny', 'myCEO']

Code Example 2: We can achieve the same as above using spread operator in JS

In [ ]:
%%script node

let oldArray = ['Mary', 'Joel', 'Danny'];

// this operation create a new array and not a pointer to oldarray 
let newArray = ["myBoss", ...oldArray, "myCEO"]

console.log('newArray:', newArray)

// note that this latest addition is not in the newArray
oldArray.push('myNeighbor')
console.log('newArray:', newArray)

newArray: [ 'myBoss', 'Mary', 'Joel', 'Danny', 'myCEO' ]
newArray: [ 'myBoss', 'Mary', 'Joel', 'Danny', 'myCEO' ]

Code Example 3: Directly refer to the array does not create a copy but only a pointer to the array

In [ ]:
%%script node

let contacts = ['Mary', 'Joel', 'Danny'];

// this does not create a copy
// but a pointer to the other array
let personalFriends = contacts; 

console.log('personalFriends:', personalFriends)
contacts.push('myBoss');

// we can confirm that this is a pointer
// because the latest push is also added
console.log('personalFriends:', personalFriends)

personalFriends: [ 'Mary', 'Joel', 'Danny' ]
personalFriends: [ 'Mary', 'Joel', 'Danny', 'myBoss' ]

Code Example 4: Using spread operator on array `[...array]` creates a copy

In [9]:
%%script node

let contacts = ['Mary', 'Joel', 'Danny'];

// this creates a copy of the `contacts` array
let personalFriends = [ ...contacts ]; 

console.log('personalFriends:', personalFriends)
contacts.push('myBoss');

// we can confirm that this is a copy
// because the latest push is not added
console.log('personalFriends:', personalFriends)

personalFriends: [ 'Mary', 'Joel', 'Danny' ]
personalFriends: [ 'Mary', 'Joel', 'Danny' ]

Code Example 5: Using spread operator on an object creates a copy of that object

In [ ]:
%%script node

let person = {
    name: "Adam",
    age: 25,
    city: "New York"
}

let employee = {

    // this copies from th eobject person
    ...person,
    salary: 50000,
    position: "Software Developer"
}


console.log('employee:', employee)

// adding new key value pair
person['hobby'] = "Climbing Mount Everest"
console.log('person:', person)

// note that the latest keyvalue pair we added to person is not in employee
// which is what we'd expect 
console.log('employee:', employee)

employee: {
  name: 'Adam',
  age: 25,
  city: 'New York',
  salary: 50000,
  position: 'Software Developer'
}
person: {
  name: 'Adam',
  age: 25,
  city: 'New York',
  hobby: 'Climbing Mount Everest'
}
employee: {
  name: 'Adam',
  age: 25,
  city: 'New York',
  salary: 50000,
  position: 'Software Developer'
}

7. Rest Operator¶

  • We use rest operator when we don't know how many arguments we will have as input to our functions.
In [37]:
%%script node

// 1. this is good for a single arg input
 
function add1(nums) {
    console.log(nums)
}

add1(4) // 4

// -------------------------------------------------
// 2. but what if we need to take in multiple inputs?
// we can use `arguments`, but it is not an array (not iterable)

function add2(nums) {
    console.log(arguments); // now deprecated unofficially
}

add2(4,5,6,7) // { '0': 4, '1': 5, '2': 6, '3': 7}


// -------------------------------------------------
// 3. This is when we use rest operator
// we will get an array

function add3(...nums) {
    console.log(nums)
}

add3(4,5,6,7) // [4, 5, 6, 7]

4
[Arguments] { '0': 4, '1': 5, '2': 6, '3': 7 }
[ 4, 5, 6, 7 ]

11. Let & Const¶

var¶

  • Variable hoisting: var is hoisted out into the outer scope.
    • We can see this in action in Code Example 1 below -- we are actually declaring and defining example variable in line 4 within the if statement but essentially what the javascript see is similar to Code Example 2 below where var example is hoisted out to line 3 before the if statement.

Code Example 1: Var variable is hoisted into the outer scope

In [ ]:
%%script node

if (false) {
    var example = 5
}

// this should be an error but we only get undefined
// because of variable hoisting
console.log(example) 

undefined

Code Example 2: What JS essentially see (var is hoisted out into the outer scope)

In [ ]:
%%script node

var example;

if (false) {
    example = 5
}

console.log(example) 

undefined

let¶

  • To workaround variable hoisting, we use let and const.
  • let is a stricter version of variable and it uses block scope.
  • If we try to recreate the above Code Example 1 using let, we will get error because the let example variable only exist within the if statement, and not out of it.
    • This is as we'd expected, because the way Javascript now sees it is essentially how we had written it.

Code Example 3: let variable only exist within the block it is defined in

In [ ]:
%%script node

if (false) {
    // example variable only exist here within this nested block of code
    let example = 5
}

// we now get an error because let variable does not exist here
console.log(example)

const¶

  • const stands for constant.
  • When set to primitive datatype (number, string, boolean), you can not change it.
  • However, when set to arrays, and object, you can still "make changes" to it. We just can't completely change it to something else;

Code Example 4: changing data stored in const variable

In [ ]:
%%script node

const myNum = 5;
// myNum = 10 // TypeError: Assignment to constant variable.

const obj = {}
obj['food'] = 'Tom Yam'
console.log(obj) // { food: 'Tom Yam' }

const arr = []
arr.push('Tom Yam')
console.log(arr) // [ 'Tom Yam' ]

{ food: 'Tom Yam' }
[ 'Tom Yam' ]

12. Import & Export¶

  • We can now export and import defined stuffs from another script (like we would do with python) in Javascript.
  • The syntax for exporting is export {}. We place a list of stuffs we want to export inside the curly braces.
  • Likewise, to import, we use import {} from x where x is the script location where we want to import it from. We put a list of stuffs we want to import in the curly braces.

13. padStart() & padEnd()¶

  • Padding to start or end of string depending on the length of the string.
In [10]:
%%script node

let example = 'coffee'; // 6 character long
console.log(example)

// 10 - 6 = 4 character of x will be added to start of string
console.log(example.padStart(10,'x')) 

// 10 - 6 = 4 character of x will be added to end of string
console.log(example.padEnd(10,'x'))

coffee
xxxxcoffee
coffeexxxx

14. Classes¶

  • this keyword in Javascript class act like the self keyword in Python.

Code Example 1: Simple class in JS

In [ ]:
%%script node

class Animal {

    constructor(type, legs) {
        this.type = type;
        this.legs = legs

    }

}

let cat = new Animal('Brown Tabby', 4);
console.log(cat)
console.log(cat.type)
console.log(cat.legs)

// we can also reset the value
cat.legs = 3
console.log(cat.legs) // now our sad cat has 3 legs

let robot = new Animal(); // we did not send any args
console.log(robot)

Animal { type: 'Brown Tabby', legs: 4 }
Brown Tabby
4
3
Animal { type: undefined, legs: undefined }

Code Example 2: Class with method

In [18]:
%%script node

class Animal {

    constructor(type, legs) {
        this.type = type;
        this.legs = legs

    }

    // define method for this class
    makeNoise(sound = 'Loud Noise') {
        console.log(sound);
    }

}


let cat = new Animal('Brown Tabby', 4)
cat.makeNoise('Meow')
cat.makeNoise()

Meow
Loud Noise

Code Example 3: Static method within a class allow us to use the method without creating an instance of the class

In [20]:
%%script node

class Animal {

    constructor(type, legs) {
        this.type = type;
        this.legs = legs

    }

    // static function
    static hiFive() {
        return 'Hi Five!';
    }

}

console.log(Animal.hiFive())

Hi Five!

Code Example 4: Using getter function in a class

In [ ]:
%%script node

class Animal {

    constructor(type, legs) {
        this.type = type;
        this.legs = legs

    }

    

    // getter function is treated like a property of our instance
    // ie cant override
    get metaData() {
        return `Type: ${this.type}, Legs: ${this.legs}`
    }


}

let cat = new Animal('Tabby Cat', 4)
console.log(cat.metaData)

// nothing will happen if we try to override getter function
cat.metaData = 'new things'
console.log(cat.metaData)

Type: Tabby Cat, Legs: 4
Type: Tabby Cat, Legs: 4

Code Example 5: Extending parent class with own constructor + overriding parent's method

In [34]:
%%script node

class Animal {

    constructor(type, legs) {
        this.type = type;
        this.legs = legs

    }

    makeNoise(sound = 'Loud Noise') {
        console.log(sound)
    }

    get metaData() {
        return `Type: ${this.type}, Legs: ${this.legs}`
    }

}


// extending parent class, with own constructor
class Dog extends Animal {
    constructor(type, legs, fierce) {
        super(type, legs);
        this.fierce = fierce;
    }

    // overriding parent's class method
    makeNoise(sound = 'woof') {
        console.log(sound)
    }
}


let dog = new Dog('Bull Dog', 4, true)
console.log(dog)
dog.makeNoise()

// we can still use method defined in parent's class
console.log(dog.metaData)

Dog { type: 'Bull Dog', legs: 4, fierce: true }
woof
Type: Bull Dog, Legs: 4

15. Promises¶

  • Promises usually used on network request eg trying to fetch some data from an API, or they could be used in asynchronous function.
  • 3 possible outcome of promises:
    • pending
    • successful
    • rejected
  • Promise takes a function. The function takes 2 parameters. Usually the parameters of the function are called resolve and reject (but we are free to call it anything we want).
    • These resolve and reject parameters takes in callback functions that will be run:
      • When the promise request is successful, the resolve callback function will be run.
      • When the promise request is rejected, the reject callback function will be run.

Example 1: Promises in asynchronous function

Code Example 2: Promise with object return value on success

In [ ]:
%%script node

const getUser = () => {
    return new Promise ((resolve, reject) => {
        
        setTimeout(() => {
            
            const error = false;
            
            if(error) {
                reject("Sorry, User 1234 is not found");
            } else {
                resolve({
                    userId: 1234,
                    name: "Lily",
                    tier: "Premium"
                })
            }
            
        }, 3000)
        
    })
}

getUser()
.then((data) => {console.log(data)})
.catch((error) => {console.log(error)})

{ userId: 1234, name: 'Lily', tier: 'Premium' }

Code Example 2: Passing parameter to Promise

  • ref: https://stackoverflow.com/a/35318609
In [ ]:

fetch('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/todos/', {

        completed: true
    })
})
    .then(response => response.json())
    .then(data => console.log(data))

16. Async & Await¶

  • By default, code is run top to bottom, synchronously.
  • It will not wait for any line of code to finish running before running the next line.
  • In some cases, this is not we want because we would want to wait for some piece of code to finish running before running the next.

Example 1: Synchronous is the default

Code Example 2: Asynchronous & await let us to wait for a piece of code to finish running before running the rest

  • We can turn a default synchronous function into a asynchronous by attaching async before the function definition.
  • We also can put await in front of a piece of code we want to wait on, before running the rest.

In [9]:
%%script node

const apiUrl = "https://api.chucknorris.io/jokes/random";

async function getJoke() {
    const response = await fetch(apiUrl);
    const data = await response.json();
    const joke = data['value'];
    console.log(joke)
    
}

getJoke()

Chuck Norris can write two-handed.

17. Sets¶

  • Same as python.

// create a new set
const a = new Set([1,
                    2,2,
                    3,3,3])

// add to set
a.add(4).add(4).add(5)
console.log(a)

// get the length of the set using `size`, not `length`(they should just use 1 for all /meh) 
console.log(a.size, a.length) 

// clear the entire set
a.clear()
console.log(a.size)
